[
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Motivation ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      100,
      191,
      158,
      213
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Compared to Euclidean convolution,existing graph convolution methods generally fail to learn diverse convolution operators under limited parameter scalesand depend on additional treatments of multi-scale feature extraction. In this paper,we want to bridge the gap between Euclidean space and graph space,and therefore generalize Euclidean convolution to graphs. ",
    "bbox": [
      14,
      225,
      245,
      323
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Generalizing Euclidean convolution to graphs faces challenges from two aspects.From the graph perspective,they generally have irregular local structures,diferent from the grid data in Euclidean space. ",
    "bbox": [
      14,
      331,
      245,
      389
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/All in a Row: Compressed Convolution Networks for Graphs_poster/visuals/images/fig_1.jpg",
    "image_caption": [
      "RegularLocal Structure "
    ],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
      28,
      407,
      132,
      539
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/All in a Row: Compressed Convolution Networks for Graphs_poster/visuals/images/fig_2.jpg",
    "image_caption": [
      "Irregular Local Structure "
    ],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
      155,
      395,
      230,
      549
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "From the Euclidean convolution perspective,it is sensitive to the local spatial order,while GNNs should preserve permutation invariance, i.e., produce the same node representations regardless of the order of the nodes. ",
    "bbox": [
      14,
      586,
      245,
      644
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/All in a Row: Compressed Convolution Networks for Graphs_poster/visuals/images/fig_3.jpg",
    "image_caption": [
      "Permutation Invariance/Equivariance "
    ],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
      18,
      654,
      243,
      806
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
