  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Regularization on Graphs ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      335,
      491,
      427,
      509
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "We propose to regularize graph-structured data through learnable permutations for end-to-end GNNs. ",
    "bbox": [
      265,
      529,
      495,
      565
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Position Regression: Nodes with similar features or short paths in between will get closer position prediction. ",
    "bbox": [
      265,
      575,
      495,
      613
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\mathbf {r} _ {A} = \\tilde {\\mathbf {A}} ^ {t} \\mathrm {M L P} (\\mathbf {X}), \\quad \\mathbf {r} = \\operatorname {s g n} \\left(\\mathbf {r} _ {A} \\mathbf {1} ^ {\\top} - \\mathbf {1 r} _ {A} ^ {\\top}\\right) \\mathbf {1}. \\tag {1}\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      310,
      618,
      495,
      641
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Weusethe sigmoid function to approximate the sign function in backpropagation. ",
    "bbox": [
      265,
      646,
      495,
      684
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Permutation Matrix Generation:We resort to the cyclic shift to generate permutation matrices. The differentiable cyclic shift can be implemented through element-wise addition and modulus. ",
    "bbox": [
      265,
      693,
      495,
      750
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\hat {\\mathbf {P}} = \\exp \\left\\{- \\tau \\left[ \\left(\\mathbf {m} \\mathbf {1} ^ {\\top} - \\mathbf {1 r} ^ {\\top} + n\\right) \\quad (\\mathrm {m o d} n) \\right] \\right\\}, \\tag {2}\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      301,
      753,
      495,
      786
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "where $\\mathbf { m } \\in \\mathbb { R } ^ { n }$ denotes the indicator,initialized as $\\pmb { \\mathsf { m } } _ { j } = j$ ， $\\tau$ denotes the relaxation factor. ",
    "bbox": [
      265,
      788,
      495,
      823
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Compressed Convolution Network ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      554,
      491,
      677,
      509
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Learnable permutations decouple the input order and the follow-up module,therefore we can apply either permutation-sensitive or permutationinvariant operators on graphs. ",
    "bbox": [
      500,
      529,
      730,
      586
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "The Compressed Convolution Network (CoCN) can be highlighted as: ",
    "bbox": [
      501,
      595,
      715,
      614
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "list",
    "sub_type": "text",
    "list_items": [
      "Diagonal convolution learns both node features and structure features explicitly. ",
      "Diagonal convolution performs diagonal sliding on structure features to adapt to the scale of graphs. ",
      "CoCNs directly apply hierarchical feature learning on graphs. ",
      "· The computational units of CoCNs are nodes/node sets. ",
      "· CoCNs use anti-diagonal compression to update structure features. "
    ],
    "bbox": [
      509,
      623,
      729,
      794
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
